reviews.review_text:
My ties with the Dead began at this 1972 show. My first Dead show. On this day I turned16. My 19-year-old brother took me to the Palladium show. Hid B-day gift was
taking me to the Palladium; buying the ticket was on me.
At first I was a bit uncomfortable with all the weird dancing.
As the show rolled on I began to understand part the the DeadHead culture; I could be "myself" at the show, no judgements or criticisms. I began to awkwardly dance but sin a short time I began to flow.
(Footnote: I thought Darkstar was boring and way too long)

Welcome to Hollywood! After more than 40 years since my last listen, I stumbled on this updated recording, hit play, and quickly remembered why it’s another standout show in a legendary year of standout shows. The major highlights for me are, no surprise: (1) the outstanding PITB, filled with Jerry’s haunting tone and frenzied wah wah work, punctuated by Bob’s sharp accents and a steady flow of intense, textured peaks. To me it has a similar feel to other strong versions from this period, e.g., 3/28/72 and 8/21/72; and (2) the expansive Dark Star, which tells its own entire kaleidoscopic musical story, with varied tempos, moods, and themes, and loaded with silky guitar runs, tight band interplay, and exploratory jamming. The rest of the show is terrific too, see, e.g., the intensity of the Truckin’ jam and the sweet, soulful beauty of the Sing Me Back Home. In short, this is another outstanding show, long overdue for official release, and you’re gonna want to hear this crisp remaster of it.
